Subsidy Traps
Cambridge, USA — No policy brings good economics into such direct conflict with good politics as do subsidies for food and energy.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue facing the three most important new leaders in the world. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President "Jokowi" Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi is facing subsidy cuts that are turning out to be better than expected.
On the contrary, Modi is facing a worse situation than expected, which could even undermine the long-awaited WTO agreement.
Meanwhile, Jokowi's situation remains unclear.
In July, Sisi accomplished a feat rarely achieved by leaders in North Africa and the Middle East: he significantly cut long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Strangely, there have been almost no protests against this.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained at extremely low levels, often used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often led to turmoil, even toppling governments.
However, the Sisi government seems to be making progress in this area as well.
Bread subsidies have been cut by 13%.
Sisi has no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year still reached 10% of GDP (which would have been 14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, almost no one expected Sisi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, to act more swiftly than Modi, who secured an overwhelming democratic majority as Prime Minister in India, where there is an urgent desire for comprehensive economic reform.
In Indonesia, Jokowi, who began governing in October, inherited long-standing fuel subsidies amounting to as much as $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government expenditure), which have already burdened the country.
The outgoing Susilo took a bold first step a year ago by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he openly stated his plan to gradually implement this over four years.
Economists confidently oppose subsidies for commodities because agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In areas where competition is not perfect, the government — not large private monopolies — is the root cause.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
The controversy caused by subsidies for food and fossil fuels is sharp because they are often implemented under the banners of the environment or equality, but in reality, they are of no help to these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies go to the poorest population, while 52.6% flow into the pockets of the richest people.
Worldwide, only far less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as evidenced by the Modi government's efforts to protect agricultural subsidies.
In fact, the Modi government vetoed the WTO compromise, undoing the most important progress in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in poor countries; at other times, they benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to have both.
As a result, India has accomplished a feat: supplying wheat to consumers at artificially low prices, while also experiencing oversupply because farmers can get high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs — electricity, water, and fertilizer — while the environment is being destroyed.
) The government has purchased large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, while the small portion of the supply available to consumers is distributed in a corrupt manner that does not meet the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and purchase reserves.
But it knows that this would violate WTO rules.
Since it is impossible to permanently change these rules, Modi simply vetoed the trade facilitation agreement that the WTO had been eagerly awaiting.
Once subsidies are implemented, it is very difficult to retract them.
When world commodity prices rise (as they did over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot insulate them from the shock.
But people accustomed to government-determined food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a very strong reason for not implementing subsidies from the outset.
However, this does not mean that maintaining subsidies is necessarily the best choice for shrewd politicians once they have been implemented.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could also erupt.
Similarly, if the growing gap ultimately leads to a further surge in retail prices, slow-moving leaders will also not benefit.
In an ideal situation, while cutting food and energy subsidies, other more efficient measures to support the lower-income population should be taken.
Developing countries have already gained considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as conditional cash transfer innovations like Mexico's Progresa-Oportunidades program and Brazil's Bolsa Família program, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification system.
However, some countries are forced to make adjustments only when budget crises arise, and they may not have the money available for transfers to alleviate the pain.
Shrewd politicians might be better off implementing unpopular adjustments right from the start of their tenure.
Both Jokowi and Sisi have adopted this approach.
However, Modi, who won a landslide election under the slogan of market reform, has already fallen behind.
